Added support for PUT requests for REST API

 - Small refactor of REST handling code to support PUT requests for setting
   signal values.
 - Updated test client page with PUT support.
 - Added simple OpenAPI 3.0 standard description of current 'v1' REST
   API implementation in 'yaml' format.

Benefit of OpenAPI is standardized format and rich tool options. As
REST API definitions become more detailed, different tools available
can generate both server and client running test mockups to excersize
API and validate it.
Also, tools can generate live documentation which can invore REST API
directly.
For demonstration of this, run VIS server. Open  'https://editor.swagger.io/'
page which is OpenAPI editor. Paste content of rest-api.yaml into (or
import) and live REST API documentation will be shown. As examples are
included in documentation by design, we can excercise API by trying
different endpoints with default example values or changing it to our
own.

Update CMake support for W3C-Visserver

Cmake support updated to more modular and streamlined organization.
Each component should have its own CMakelists.txt file with local setup.

* Refactored existing Cmake build to modularize build (core, testclient,
  unit-tests, ...). Build is now cleaner and allows for simplified
  extension with new elements.
* Boost dependencies are now dynamically linked to speed-up build time and allow
  for easier re-use in other projects.
* Both static and dynamic libraries are built for core w3c-server functionality.
* Breaking change: Due to change in CMake setup, location of built executables
  is now changed in CMake build directory. Output reflect original
  sub-component location (e.g. w3c-visserver executable is located in build/src,
  unit-tests under build/unit-test directory, ...)
* Unit tests now use separate vss JSON file to remove dependency from
  other modules. w3cunittest.cpp now uses mock for actual server
  instance, as it is not needed for test execution.
* Updated README.md with relevant changes

__main__: Remove no-op call to build_package_protos()

build_package_protos() accepts a root directory path not a path to a
single proto file so currently, the code does nothing. Also, generating
_pb2 modules from proto files should remain a "setup" or "build" step
thing to do.

This also removes the runtime dependency to grpcio-tools.
Reorganize modules to split responsabilities

setup: Stop patching generated pb2 modules

Relative imports have proven flawed with protoc code generation so let
us rely on absolute ones and stop patching to enforce relative ones.
setup.py: Make sure to build protos whenever needed

setup: Move setuptools configurations to config files

- setup_requires is deprecated thus moving its content into pyproject.toml's "[build-system] requires".
- Only keep setuptools-git-versioning's options where values are different from default ones.

setup: Do not use include_package_data = True

'include_package_data = True' is incompatible with
'options.package_data'. The former considers all non .py files where the
latter specifies which files to include. Where building the project with
both options works, it generates unnecessary warnings which can be
avoided by choosing one over the other e.g.:

SetuptoolsDeprecationWarning:
Installing 'kuksa_certificates.jwt' as data is deprecated, please list it in `packages`.
.gitignore: Ignore files generated by protoc
__main__: Allow user to select which server to connect to by default

KuksaGrpcComm: Wait for channel to be connected

Otherwise, the channel might be idle and we would then tell the user
that it is connected when it's not.
README.md: Add Troubleshooting section

kuksa-client: Make Ctrl-D stop kuksa-client

Ctrl-D closes stdin which in turn makes cmdloop() return.
do_quit() is not called in this case.
This meant that the client thread would still be lying around and the
main thread would then wait forevever for its termination.
Move the exit logic outside of do_quit() to make sure we stop the client
thread no matter how we exited the command loop.

Enforce authorization

Parsing JWT access tokens and making them available as `Permissions` in
the GRPC handling code of databroker was previously implemented.

This commit adds the enforcement of these permissions throughout databroker.

This was accomplished by introducing two new interfaces
`DatabaseReadAccess` and `DatabaseWriteAccess` that can only be created
by supplying a `Permissions` struct.

All functions that read / write or create entries can only be accessed
through these interfaces (structs).

In addition, `authorized_access(Permissions) -> AuthorizedAccess` has
been added to the top level `DataBroker` interface in order to provide a
convenient way to set the permissions once, and use the wrapper
functions (in `AuthorizedAccess`) to interact with the previously
mentioned interfaces.
